        Misleading Advertising in Queensland Real Estate: What Sellers and Agents Cannot Say
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The Australian Consumer Law and Queensland's Property Occupations Act set clear limits on what can be said in a real estate listing. Here is what sellers need to know before they approve their advertising copy.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers focus their energy on presentation, pricing, and timing. The advertising copy tends to get less scrutiny, often approved in a rush before the photography goes live. That is a mistake, because the claims made in a real estate listing are governed by law, and both the agent and the seller can be held responsible for misleading representations. Understanding what you cannot say, and what your agent cannot say on your behalf, is a practical part of protecting yourself through the sales campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework</h2>
      <p>Two overlapping laws apply to Queensland real estate advertising. The Australian Consumer Law (ACL), which is a national framework, prohibits misleading or deceptive conduct in trade or commerce. Real estate transactions fall squarely within that scope. On top of that, the Property Occupations Act 2014 (Qld) imposes specific obligations on licensees, meaning agents and their agencies, including requirements to act honestly and to not engage in conduct that is likely to mislead buyers or sellers about the value or characteristics of a property.</p>

      <p>The ACL is broader than many people realise. It does not require intent to deceive. A representation that is objectively likely to mislead a reasonable person can constitute a breach, even if the person making it believed it was accurate. This is why casual exaggeration in advertising copy is riskier than it might seem.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What counts as misleading</h2>
      <p>Price representations are the most commonly scrutinised category. Queensland does not have specific underquoting legislation equivalent to Victoria's or New South Wales's, which prescribe exactly how price ranges must be set and advertised. But the ACL still prohibits a price range that is knowingly set below what the seller would actually accept. Advertising a property at "offers over $900,000" when the seller has made clear they will not consider anything under $1.1 million is a representation likely to mislead buyers about the realistic price point, and it can attract complaints and investigations.</p>

      <p>Beyond price, the categories that generate the most complaints in Queensland real estate include: unverifiable superlatives such as "best street in the suburb" or "unrivalled views", which are almost impossible to substantiate and which buyers can later argue created a false impression; false or inflated statements about recent comparable sales, rental income, or current buyer interest levels; descriptions of location or size that are technically accurate but contextually misleading (describing a property as "moments from the CBD" when it is a 35-minute drive in traffic); and condition representations that overstate the standard of finish or the currency of improvements.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The "offers over" convention</h2>
      <p>This is worth examining specifically because it is so common in Queensland advertising. Using "offers over" with a stated price creates an implied representation that offers at or near that price will be genuinely considered. If an agent consistently invites offers over a figure and then systematically rejects all offers anywhere near that figure, that pattern can constitute a misleading representation about the seller's actual price expectations.</p>

      <p>This does not mean "offers over" advertising is inherently problematic. It is standard practice and used appropriately when the seller genuinely is open to offers in the range the price suggests. The problem arises when it is used as a bait figure designed to generate enquiry at a price point the seller has no real intention of accepting. Buyers who have wasted time, conveyancing costs, and building inspection fees on a property they were never realistically able to purchase have grounds to complain under the ACL.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Photography, virtual staging, and AI enhancement</h2>
      <p>This is a growing area of regulatory attention. Digital alteration of property photographs, removing powerlines, adding grass where there is bare dirt, replacing a grey overcast sky with a bright blue one, is increasingly common and increasingly scrutinised. The ACCC and state consumer agencies have made clear that photographs which materially misrepresent the property's appearance or condition can constitute misleading conduct.</p>

      <p>Standard editing adjustments, correcting lens distortion, adjusting exposure, removing a rubbish bin from the verge, sit within generally accepted practice. But alterations that change how a reasonable buyer would assess the property itself, improving views, removing neighbours' structures, adding features that do not exist, cross into territory that creates legal risk. Virtual staging, where digitally rendered furniture is added to empty rooms, is widely accepted provided it is disclosed. An empty room advertised with virtual furniture as if it were real staging is more problematic.</p>

      <p>AI-enhanced photography is the newest frontier in this area. Tools that can transform an average exterior shot into something resembling a styled professional photograph are increasingly accessible. Where those enhancements create a materially false impression of a property's presentation or condition, they carry real risk under the ACL.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers are responsible for</h2>
      <p>This is the part that surprises many vendors. The common assumption is that misleading advertising is the agent's problem, since they wrote the copy. But that is not how the law works. Sellers who review and approve their agent's advertising share responsibility for the representations it contains. The ACL applies to the vendor as well as the licensee. A seller who approves copy they know to be false or exaggerated cannot later disclaim responsibility on the basis that the agent wrote it.</p>

      <p>This is a practical reason to take advertising review seriously, not as a formality but as a genuine check. If something in the copy makes a claim you cannot verify, query it before approving. If your agent has included a statement about buyer interest levels or comparable sales that you cannot confirm, ask where it came from. If a description overstates an aspect of the property, ask for it to be amended. Your agent should welcome this level of engagement, because it protects both of you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical steps for sellers</h2>
      <p>Read your listing copy carefully before it goes live. Not as a matter of pride or aesthetic preference, but as a substantive review of every factual claim the copy makes. Ask yourself: is this verifiable? Is this accurate? Would a buyer feel misled if they discovered it was not true? If the answer to any of those questions is uncertain, push back before approving.</p>

      <p>Be particularly careful with any claim about price expectations, buyer activity, comparable sales, or the physical condition and features of the property. These are the categories that attract the most complaints and create the most liability exposure. A good agent will be able to substantiate every factual claim in the copy, and if they cannot, that is a reason to remove it rather than leave it in on the basis that it sounds reasonable.</p>

      <p>Finally, do not pressure your agent to overstate the property or to set an "offers over" figure that you have no genuine intention of accepting in order to maximise enquiry volume. The short-term benefit of broader enquiry is not worth the legal and reputational exposure, and it wastes buyers' time in a way that can damage your negotiating position if those buyers later feel misled and withdraw from the process.</p>

